{"/service/ndnp/wa/batch_wa_kingfisher_ver02/data/sn87093407/00340585446/1924010201/0896.xml":{"full_text":"18\nTHE STAR\u2019S PAGE OF NEWS FOID BUSINESS MEN\nRailroads Make Double Ap\npeal in Series\nA double-barreled campalgn, aimed\n@t both the farmers and the manu\nfacturers of the nation, Is the next\ngtep In the series of advertising of\nthe Pacific Northwest being conduot\ned by the Great Northern, Northern\nPacifio and the Chicago, Burlington\nQuincy rallroads. One advertise\nment of the stata of Washington,\n\u201cWhere Farming Is a Better Paying\nBusiness,\u201d will go into 19 farm mag:\nazines with a combined circulation\n\"of over three and a half milllons,\nwhile \u201cThe Story of the Pucific\nWorthwest Citles\u201d will appear in\nother national magasines with a com-\nbined circulation of over nine mil\u2019\nlons,\nFor the farmer, the advertisements\n1 will tell a number of Interesting facts\nabout Washington as a farming\ni state, Among them are these:\nWashington's average acre yield of\nwheat is 20 per cent higher than the\npation average, and its yield of hay\nX is 50 per cent greater,\ni The yields of its orchards are the\nbighest In the United States,\nThe value of its hogs, per 100\npounds, is 16 per cent greater than\nthe national average, and the weight\ni per fleece of its wool Is 15 per cent\ngreater,\nIts Dhighly developed poultry In.\ndustry {s unexcelled in unit produc\ntion, quantity of favorable conditions.\nIn the storles of the Pacific North.\nWrest cities, tho only the larger citles\nare featured, the text speaks, in the\nmaln, in the terms of all of them.\nThe citles that are featured, one In\n_#ach advertisement, are Spokane,\n*\u201cThe Heart of the Inland Empire,\u201d\nTacoma, \u201cThe City With a Mountain\nIn Its Dooryard,\u201d PFortland, *\u201cThe\nCity of Roses,\u201d and \u201cSeattle, \u201cThe\nGateway to the Orfent.\u201d\n\"Know Seattle,\u201d says the fext.\n*Forty years ago frontier settle.\nment without a railroad and with but\none crude dock, Today a great world\nport, terminus of four transcontinen\ntal rallroads, gateway to the vast\ncommerce of the Orient, and market\nplace for Alaska. In 1900 a town of\n80,000, Today a metropolitan city of\n360,000, and the largest city of its\nAge in the Unitel States.\n\u201cKnow Seattle\u2014and you know all\nof the scores of thriving, prosperous\ncities that dot the Pacific Northwest.\nCitles young, energetic, growing in.\ndustrially and commercially with a\nswiftness that spells OPPORTUNITY\ni \u2014the greatest opportunity offered by\nany section of the country today.\u201d\n1\n\nSeattle Bankers Will Attend\u2018\nMeeting at Yakima\nM. F. Backus, president of the\nBeattle Clearing House' association,\nbas appointed E. Shorrock of the Ma.\nrine National bank, and C. H. Howell\nof the Seaboard Nationai bank, to\nrepresent the Seattle banks at the\nmeeting to be held In Yakima Janu\nary 16 and 17, to discuss the apple\nmarketing situation of the North\nwest. This me\u00e9ting has been called\nby the Washington stats chamber\nof commerce with the expectation\nof getting all of the elements of the\napple marketing situation together\nand working out some marketing\nmethod which will do away with\nthe present market gluts, consign.\nments and rejections.\nBankers thruout the state have\nghown a live interest in the apple\nmarketing situation calling attention\nto the fact that there {8 the funda.\nmental question of finance to be\nworked out in addition to the grow.\ners\u2019 problems, distribution, ware.\nhousing and advertising. The pro\ngram for the meeting as at present\noutlined will only Include two\nspeeches, an address of welcoms by\nGovernor Hart and a talk by a\nmarketing expert, following which\nall of the time will be spent In com\nmittes work.\n\nLions\u2019 Club Will\n\nUrge Registration\nThe regular meeting of the Se\nattle Lions\u2019 club on January 7 will\nbe devoted to the opening of a cam\npaign to get citizens to register for\nand vote at the coming elections,\nMatt Hill, deputy United States at\ntorney, will be the principal speaker,\nand county Auditor D. E, Ferguson\nwill demonstrate the use of voting\nmachines,\nFinancial Flashes\nFrom James Macfariane o,\n\u00a5il Recond Ave.\nTwenty industrial stocks average\n$5.23, an increase of .11; 20 rall stocks\nsverage 80.63, an increase of .52; 40\nbonds average 86.61, an increase of\nSl\nFavorable Industrial prediec\ntions for 1921 were the outstand\ning features of the week-end\nnews, stimulating the early de\nmand for stocks. oOil shares were\nespecially benefitted by 15-cent\nadvance in Eastern crude prices,\nAltho word has gone out from sev\neral sources that a slight decline may\nbe expected in the volume of freight\ntraffic next year, there is likelihood\n<hat upward revision will have to be\nwade before the year s far advanced.\nSecy. Wallace, in review of the\nyear from an agricultural stand\npoint, announced that conditions\nauger well for cortinued improve\nment in the material prosperity\nof the American farmer,\nMontgomery Ward December sales\n$15,082,713 versus $11,629,292 in De\ncember, 1922, 12 months, $134,0644,436\nworsus 302,474,152,\nBrokers look for marked im\nrovement in security prices after\nthe turn of the year,\nHupp Motor has called for redemp\ntion April first, all outstanding pre\nferred at 120 and accrued dividends.\nAfter that dividends will cease and\nmtockholders\u2019 rights on this lssue end.\nJohn Moody Prophesies\nProsperity During 1924\nGood Times Will Last for Period of\nTwo or Three Years\nBY ALEXANDER HERMAN\n(Copyright, 1924, by NEA Service)\nNEW YORK, Jan, 2.--Heroe's a\nbusiness and financial forecast\nmada by John Moody, analyst, who\nprobably has a closer touch on the\npulse of business conditions than any\nother man in the country:\n1924--On the whole, a constructive\nyear, with business good and mark.\ning the beginning of a perlod of\nlonger prosperity,\nMoody 18 not swayed by sentiment,\nCold faots are his fodder.\n\u201cSpeaking broadly,\u201d he says, I\n;look upon 1924 with considerable op\ntimism. We will find {t, on the\nwhole, a constructive year, with the\nrapidity of progress depending some.\nwhat on political developments,\n1S OPTIMISTIC\nFOR COMING YEAR\n\u201cThere are certain fundamental\nfacts that Indicate the posaibiiities\nfor a good year. For the past six\nmonths or more we have been In a\nperiod of more or less financial con.\ntraction. A study of the financlal\nexhibits shows that bank mcms}\nare belng built up; merchants' lia.\nbilitles are not greatly expanding:\nthere are no longer great inflated in..\nventories of the type of 1020; Inter.\nest rates are relatively low and\nhave been tending to remain so all\nthe fall, the season when the usual.\nly tighten up.\n\u201cNotwithstanding the activity In\nbusiness, reserves are being bullt up,\nwhich are the usual forerunners of\na period of prosperity, The notion\nwhich provalled a year ago, that\nwe might run Into a new period of\ninflation, has not been borne out by\nthe facts,\n\u201cFor blg business has been acting\nmore cautiously than 1t did during\nthe period of wild Inflation In 1919\nand 1820, There has been little\ntendency to over-expand and stock\nup with goods In anticlpation of a\nboom. Most business men stil! re\nmember the amash of 1920 and have\nlearned a lesson {n caution.\n\u201cAll these primary factors make\nfor healthy conditions for the Inaug.\nuration of new perfod of prosper.\nity immediately ahead of us, There\nmay be only moderate evidence of\nthis business revival unt!l the mid.\ndle of the new year. But If thers ia\na declded promise of tax reduction,\nand other constructive political de\nvelopments take place, real business\nrevival may be evident much earlier.\nLike everything else, psychological\nfactors enter Into business condl\ntions.\u201d\nThen, taking up the leading Indus.\nLirien, Moody sald this:\nMANY LINES ARE\nBETTER OFF\n\u201cFarmers: Agrfcviture has been\nbehind the procession for several\nyears but the farmers are, ony the\nwhole, better off than they were a[\nyear or two ago. This improve\nment should continue during 1924\nif weather conditlons prove favor.\nable and markets do not contract\nto any great extent.\n\"Foreign Situation: Getting ma_i\nfly better, for the economle cond!.\ntion of the people In mest of\nEurope is slowly improving. During\n1924 the reparations problem may\nbe brought closer to a permanent\nsettlement,\n\u201cRallroads: The greatest trouble\nfor the raflroads Is that they are\nburdened with the United States\ngovernment as their senior part.\nner. As a whole, the rallroads are\ntoday belng operated as efficlently\nas they can be under present dif.\nficult conditions.\n\u201cBasic Industries: The steel in.\ndustry has been operating on small\nmargins of profit and s consid.\nerably depressed; the copper infus.\ntry shows some signs of improve\nment; the leather industry s in bad\n-Mgo: textiles are somewhat better,\nbut\u00aethe outlook for the rubber in.\ndustry is not so good. The auto\nmobile Industry seems overdevel\noped, but demand continues to\nstimulate supply.\n\u201cLabor: 1 ses no prospect of radl\ncal wags reductions during the\ncoming yedr, The prevalllng short.\nags of labor in nearly all lines\nseems certain to keep wages atable,\n\u201cThe Question of Deflatian: T do\nnot think that the trend of com\nmodity prices is golng to be notice.\nably downward for a number of\nyearas to come. The {dea of return.\ning to the basis of 1013 In commod.\nity prices and the e\u00dfst of living, is\nsteadily becoming less likely. Costa\nare abnormal, compared with pre.\nwar times, In all parta of the world,\nbut, like everything else, when peo\nple have adjusted themselves to an\nabnormal situation long enough, it\ngraduvally becomes recognized as the\nnormal situation.\nSEES PROSPERITY FOR\nTWO OR THREE YEARS\n\u201cLooking ahead: 'The expected\nperiod of prosperity which should de\nvelop in 1924 may run for a year or\nperhaps two or three years. Its\n'lnng'h will be dependent, to a large\nextent, on developments In the field\nof foreign affairs.\n\u201cIf theso foreign developments\ntake shape as now anticipated, it s\nvery possibla that by 1927 Ameriea\nmay run into a long perlod of unset.\nMODERN ELECTRIC\nSAFE DEPOSIT\nEQUIPMENT\nT e ...\"\"\"\".\u2018.\"L(..rL\nb e G 4]\nl 'J,l\"y\u2019y'-(\nYRV\n(il 1Y et d\n5 o dey sMo\n)ft\u2018v\u2019.i i\u00ab\n1 (A is a)iie\u2019d\nA\nB 'q vl,_:, \u2018l\nB RiA\n4\u00ab\"- .-w\nbR igat %&1. ke\nSEATTLE NATIONAL:\nb BANK\nIt A\nJohn Moody\ntlament and depression. The reason\nfor this is not far to seek.\n\u201cRy 1027, or thereabouts, Buropean\nconditions will have become far more\nstabilized; Germany will be bullding\nup production In enormous volume\nin order to meet reparations pay.\nments; the allied countries will also\nbe bullding up production In \u2018great\nvolume to meet payments to the\nUnited States on the interallied\ndebta, The necessity of meoting\ntheso debta will prove to be a stimu\nlant for Increasing production in all\nparts of Europe,\nYlt Germany is to pay the allles\nand It the allies are to pay us, these\npayments can take only one form;\nthat of the shipment of goods In\nenormous volume Into this country.\nBecause of the low cost labor of Eu.\nrope, which will continue to be meas\n|urod by Infiated currencies, it will\nbe practically impossible for the\nUnited States to radically curtall Eu.\nropean imports,\n\u201cThe only way shs could change\nthis development would be thru\nsome plan for the reduction, indefl.\nnite extension or cancellation of the\ninterallied debts. Or, this condition\ncould be partially offset by the In.\n[vuaunmt of American capital itself\nIn enormous volume In European\nproducing industries.\u201d\nSnohomsih Cow Men\n\nElect New Officers\nBILVANA, Jan. 2.-At the annual\nmeeting of the Snohomish County\nCow Testing association steps were\ntaken to Inerease the membership,\nOtficers for the new year Include K.\nT. Knutson of BSllvana, president;\nHans Thomsen of Ariington, vice\npresident, and J. B. Wrage of Arling\nton, secretary-treasurer, The board\nof directors will consist of the three\nofficers and F, H. Nistfield of Maryns\nville and B. A. Barker of Snohomish,\n\n\u201curesu Report\nTATOOSH ISLAND, Jan. 2.8 m.\u2014\nBaromater falling. Cloudy; wind east,\n3% miles an hour.\n\n\nArrivals and Departures\nArrived\u2014Jan. 1.--Btr Seckonk from\n\u2019aomm via ports, at 7:30 p. m.; str Vi\nking from Tacoma, at 1:18 p. m.; sir\nRuth Alsxander from Han Diego via Han\nFrancisco atd Los Angeles, at 1 p. m.;\nmotorship Charile Watson from lieh\nmond via Astoria, st 11 a. m.\nSalled-\u2014Jan, I\u2014Btr Ruth Alexander\nfor Tacoma, at Tp. m.; str Hambleton\nRange for Kobe via poris, at 1:15 p. m.;\n#tr Curacos for Anacortes via ports, at\n12130 p. m.; etr Kinryo mary for Osaka\nvia ports, at 3:390 a. m,\nL\n\nVessels in Port at Seattle\nBraith Cove Terminal\u2014Pler \u00a7l-\u2014Btr Bhid.\ngouka Maru. Pier 40-Btr Cross Keys\nBell Htreet Terminal-U. 8. J. H. T,\nHeather, U. 8. C. O. Unalga, Bncho\nmish,\nPler 14\u20148 tr Protesilaus,\nPler 118-Ma George Washington, strs\nOwego, Madison.\nPler \u00a7\u2014Btr Brookdale,\n;Pler 6--Btr Viking.\nPler 2-<Btr Alaska.\nPlar D\u2014#Bir Admiral Rodman,\nBeattle Bhipbullding Dry Dock Co.=\nHitr Oreus,\nil\"-el\ufb02e Coast Coal Dunkers\u2014U. 8. 1. 8.\nRellef,\nConnecticut Btreet Terminal\u2014U,\nDiscoverer, ma \u00a5Frank Lynch, U, 8, E,\nPloneer, str Commarelal Hpirit.\nAtlantic Htreet Terminal--Btr Seekonk.\nStandard Ol Co's Terminal\u2014Btr Pana\nman, U, B B Burveyor,\nKing Winge\u2014~Bchr Ruby, ma Anvil, 4\nHauford BStreet Terminal\u2014Btr Tokiwa\nMaru,\nBpokana Strest Terminal\u2014Btr Narenta, i\nEast Waterway Dock Warehouse Ca.l\n~Hirs West Jappa, Jacob Luckenbach,\nGeneral Petroleum Terminal\u2014#tr Presl\ndent Jackson,\nTodd Dry Doc