nicating\nservice between the two medical\nbuilding, which will add to thelir ef\nficlency In every respect.\nThe building will be ready for oc.\ncupancy September 1, and 2 largs\npart of the space has already been\nleased to prominent medical men.\nTry to Eliminate Ship Mes\nsage Interference\nA conference of radio and steam.\nship companies has been called for\nJanuary by O. R. Redfern, U, 8\nSupervisor of radio, to meet at 10\na.m, in the office of the radio in\nspector at 2501 L. C. Smith bullding,\nThe conference will consider the\nquestion of remedies for Interference\nbetween concerts and reports of ship\npositions, s\n\u201cIt is believed,\u201d Redfern says,\n\u201cthat if these ship reports could be\ntransmitted by the ships before\n6 p. m., or after 11 p. m., the present\ninterference caused with the recep.\ntion of broadcasting concerts would\nbe reduced 75 per cent.\u201d This stale\nment is made after being informed\nby commercial coast stations that\nper cent of the traffic they handie\nduring that time consists of position\nreports,\nThe department of commerce was\nadvised of this condition and in reply\nthey requested that a conference be\nheld of commercial radio companles\nand steamship companies for the pur\npose of determining whether or not\nit was feasible to have these posi.\ntion reports transmitted before 7 p. m,\nor after 11 p. m.\n\u201cAn effort is to be made to se\ncure new radio legislation during the\npresent session of congress, and the\nopinion of all interested is desired as\nto the advisability of discontinuing\nthe use of 300 and 450 meter wave\nlengths and instead of these wave\nlengths provide wave lengths for ship\n%spurk stations above 600 meters.\u201d\ng iy\n1\nIncrease Yield Per\nAcre on Beet Land\nMONTESANO, Jan. 2.\u2014Checking\non a fertilization demonstration con\nducted by County Agent Robert\n]Cowun. of Grays Harbor country,\njan increase of four tons per acre\n{of beets was mado by adding 100\ni pounds of potash and 200 pounds\ni of phosphate per acre together with\nmanure, The check was made with\nthe same kind of land which had\nbeen manured but which had not\nbeen treated with potash and phos\nphate.\nDalrying\u2014Utensils should be rinsed\nwith cool or lukewarm water, then\nwashed with hot water containing\nwashipg powder, then rinsed in hot\nwater and then sterilized in hot\nwater and finally sterilized with\nsteam or by bolling 15 minutes.","height":"30644","width":"23208"}}
